{"title_page": "Economy of Chennai", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{essay-like|date=September 2012}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2007}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Tidel Park Chennai.jpg|thumb|200px|Tidel Park, one of the largest software parks in India]]\n\n[[File:Madras Port In 1996.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The [[Chennai Port]], one of the biggest in South Asia]]\n[[File:Infosys Mcity, Building number 5.jpg|thumb|right|200 px|The [[Infosys]] Building in [[Mahindra World City, New Chennai]]]]\n\n'''Chennai''', the capital city of the state of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]], is the largest industrial and commercial center of [[South India]]. Recent estimates of the economy of the [[Chennai Metropolitan Area]] have ranged from US$79 to US$86 billion ([[Purchasing power parity|PPP]] [[Gross domestic product|GDP]]), ranking it [[List of cities by GDP|from fourth to sixth most productive metro area]] of India,<ref name=\"Brookings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/research/global-metro-monitor/|title=Global city GDP 2014|publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"pricewater\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukmediacentre.pwc.com/imagelibrary/downloadMedia.ashx?MediaDetailsID=1562|title=Global city GDP rankings 2008-2025|publisher=[[Pricewaterhouse Coopers|PwC]]|accessdate=16 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504031739/https://www.ukmediacentre.pwc.com/imagelibrary/downloadMedia.ashx?MediaDetailsID=1562|archive-date=4 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"McKinsey\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/08/13/the_most_dynamic_cities_of_2025|title=The Most Dynamic Cities of 2025|publisher=Foreign Policy|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref>\nand the [[List of Indian cities by GDP (per capita)|third highest]] by GDP per capita.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raghavan|first1=T.C.A. Sharad|title=Linking urban India to drive growth|url=http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/VZ2ZW6DSRqTj7PIxbVLcIK/Linking-urban-India-to-drive-growth.html|website=livemint|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref> The metropolitan area doesn't include the nearby industrial zones of [[Sholinganallur]], [[Siruseri]], [[Oragadam]] and [[Sriperumbudur]], due to which these regions' economy doesn't get included in the total economy of Chennai. If these regions are included, the economy of chennai would be somewhere around $167 billion to $210 billion.\n\n[[Chennai]] has an economic base anchored by the automobile, [[software|software services]], [[medical tourism]], hardware manufacturing and [[financial services]]. Other important industries include petrochemicals, textiles and apparels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifeinchennai.com/chennai_economy.htm|title=Chennai|publisher=lifeinchennai.com|accessdate=27 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805174537/http://www.lifeinchennai.com/chennai_economy.htm|archive-date=5 August 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Chennai Port]] and [[Ennore Port]] contribute greatly to its importance. The city had a fully computerised stock exchange called the [[Madras Stock Exchange]].\n\nChennai was recently rated as having the highest quality of life among Indian cities ahead of the other three metros and Bangalore, based on the \"Location Ranking Survey\" conducted by ECA International. Chennai has improved its global ranking to 138 in 2006\u201307 from 179 in 2002\u201303. It is now ranked at 26th position in Asia in terms of livability, up from 31st rank in 2002\u201303.<ref name=\"livability_survey\">{{cite news | title=5 cities improve their rankings: Survey | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/5_cities_improve_rankings_in_living_standards/articleshow/1764200.cms |work=The Economic Times |location=India |date=15 March 2007 |accessdate=8 March 2007 }}</ref> According to a 2007 worldwide quality of life survey done by [[Mercer Human Resource Consulting|Mercer]], Chennai received the second highest rating in India,<ref name=\"prnewswire2007\">{{cite news | title = Worldwide Quality of Living Survey| url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/04-02-2007/0004557404&EDATE= | publisher=PRNewswire |date=2 April 2007 | accessdate = 16 April 2007}}</ref> with New Delhi scoring the highest,<ref name=\"prnewswire2007\"/> and came in at a relatively low 157th worldwide.<ref name=\"prnewswire2007\"/> The reason was attributed to poor health and sanitation, and the increasing air pollution.<ref name=\"mercer2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mercerhr.com/referencecontent.jhtml?idContent=1173105#sanitation|title=Mercer - Our Thinking, Insights, and Perspectives}}</ref> It has the distinction of being called as the [[Automotive industry in Chennai|Detroit of Asia]].\n\nAs of 2012, the city has about 34,260 identified companies in its 15 zones. Of these, 5,196 companies has a paid-up capital of over {{INR}} 5 million, about 16,459 companies are in the paid up capital range of {{INR}} 100,000 to {{INR}} 200,000, and 2,304 companies have a paid-up capital of less than {{INR}} 100,000.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Company tax upped, capped at Rs. 30,000\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | publisher = The Hindu\n | date = 30 October 2012\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/company-tax-upped-capped-at-rs-30000/article4044728.ece\n | accessdate = 30 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Software and Software Services==\n{{see also|List of tech parks in Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Salai|SEZ Corridor}}\n[[File:Zoho headquarters in chennai.jpg|thumb|Zoho Headquarters in Chennai]]\n\nSince the late 1990s, software development and [[business process outsourcing]] and more recently electronics manufacturing have emerged as major drivers of the city's economic growth. Chennai has been rated as the most attractive Indian city for offshoring services according to [[A.T. Kearney|A T Kearney's]] Indian City Services Attractiveness Index 2005.<ref name=\"most_attractive\">{{cite news | title=Chennai most attractive city for offshoring services | url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2006/04/02/stories/2006040202550100.htm |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |date=2 April 2006 |accessdate=8 March 2007 }}</ref> Major software and software services companies including [[Altran]], [[Accenture]], [[Cognizant]], [[Capgemini]], [[DXC Technology]], [[SAP SE]], [[Oracle Corporation]], [[Cisco Systems]], [[HCL Technologies]], [[Hewlett Packard Enterprise]], [[IBM]], [[CGI Inc.]], [[Infosys]], [[Sopra Steria]], [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]], [[Tata Consultancy Services]], [[Verizon]], [[Wipro]], [[Virtusa]], [[UST Global]], [[Atos]], [[Dassault Syst\u00e8mes]], [[Fujitsu]], [[NTT DATA]], [[Larsen & Toubro Infotech|LTI]], [[Honeywell]], [[VMware]], [[Intel]], [[Amazon.com|Amazon.com, Inc.]], [[Tech Mahindra]], [[Fiserv]], [[Adobe Systems]], [[AT&T]], [[Philips]], [[AstraZeneca]], [[Wolters Kluwer]], [[TransUnion]], [[Ernst & Young]], [[L&T Technology Services]], [[Mindtree]], [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell Business Operations]], [[athenahealth]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford Global Technology & Business Center]], BORN, [[Ramco Systems]], [[Deloitte]], [[Microsoft]], [[Temenos Group|Temenos]], [[Synechron Inc|Synechron]], [[KPMG]], [[PayPal]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paypal.com/il/webapps/mpp/jobs/locations|title=Jobs by location {{!}} PayPal Jobs - PayPal|website=www.paypal.com|language=en-IL|access-date=2018-05-25}}</ref> have development centres in the city. The city is now the second largest exporter of IT and IT enabled Services in the country behind [[Bangalore]]. The IT Corridor, on Old Mahabalipuram Road in the southeast of the city houses several technology parks, and, when completed, will provide employment to close to 300,000 people. Besides the existing [[Tidel Park]], two more [[Tidel Park]]s are on the anvil in the IT corridor. One is under construction at the Siruseri IT [[Special Economic Zone]] (\"SEZ\") and the other one is being planned at the current location of MGR Film City which is just before the existing [[Tidel Park]], in Taramani on the IT Corridor. A number of SEZ have emerged in and around Chennai. The [[Mahindra World City, New Chennai]], a [[Special Economic Zone|Special Economic Zone (SEZ)]] with one of the world's largest high technology business zones, is currently under construction in the outskirts of Chennai. It also includes the World's largest IT Park by Infosys.<ref name=\"infosys\">{{cite web | title= World's Largest IT Campus | work=Infosys, Mahindra World City | url=http://www.tn.gov.in/pressclippings/hindu26022004/hindu260204.htm| accessdate=6 August 2005 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050406014540/http://www.tn.gov.in/pressclippings/hindu26022004/hindu260204.htm  |archivedate = 6 April 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Electronics Hardware==\n{{main|EMS Industry in Chennai}}\n{{see also|Electronics Corridor}}\nIn recent years, [[Chennai]] has emerged as an electronic manufacturing hub in [[South Asia]] with multinational corporations like [[Dell]], [[Motorola]], [[Cisco]], [[Samsung]], [[Siemens AG|Siemens]], [[Ericsson]], [[Emerson Electric]], [[ABB Group|ABB]] and [[Flex (company)|Flex]] setting up Electronics / Hardware manufacturing plants, particularly in the [[Sriperumbudur]] electronics [[Special Economic Zone|SEZ]] . accounting for the sector alone has created investments worth $3.5bn in [[Chennai]]. Chennai is currently the largest electronics hardware exporter in India, accounting for 45% of the total exports in 2010\u201311.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.escindia.in/uploads/OVERALL%20ELECTRONICS%20HARDWARE%20EXPORT%202010-11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102191958/http://www.escindia.in/uploads/OVERALL%20ELECTRONICS%20HARDWARE%20EXPORT%202010-11.pdf |archivedate=2 January 2014}}</ref> The Government of [[India]] has planned to promote [[Chennai]] as the Electronic Manufacturing and R&D Hub of the World in a span of 15 years. [[Ericsson]],<ref name=\"Ericsson India Private Ltd. \">[http://www.ericsson.com/in/ericsson/corporate_information/ericsson_india.shtml Ericsson India Private Ltd] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107015922/http://www.ericsson.com/in/ericsson/corporate_information/ericsson_india.shtml |date=7 November 2007 }}</ref> [[Alcatel Mobile Phones|Alcatel]], [[Atmel]], [[Texas Instruments]], [[Foxconn]], [[Robert Bosch GmbH]], [[Microchip Technology]], [[Xerox]], [[Nokia Corporation]], [[Siemens]] have research and development facilities in the city . Semiconductor companies like SPEL and Tessolve have announced plans to set up or expand manufacturing and R&D centers in the city. Companies like [[Flex (company)|Flex]], [[Motorola]], [[Ericsson]], [[Samsung]], [[Cisco]] and [[Dell]] have chosen Chennai as their South Asian manufacturing hub. Chinese smartphone maker [[Huawei]] plans to their manufacturing unit in Chennai. Products manufactured include circuit boards and cellular phone handsets.<ref name=\"Flextronics\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/10/07/stories/2005100702790400.htm|title=Flextronics signs pact for Chennai facility|work=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref>[[Sanmina-SCI]] is the latest company to invest in Chennai to create a state of the art manufacturing facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconindia.com/shownews/36208|title=Welcome to the silicon india network}}</ref> [[Nokia Networks]] has decided to build a manufacturing plant for wireless network equipment in Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nokiasiemensnetworks.com/global/Press/Press+releases/news-archive/Nokia_Siemens_Networks_to_invest_USD_100_million_to_strengthen.htm|title=This domain is no more in use}}</ref>\n\n==Engineering Procurement and Construction==\n[[File:L&T Construction Head office chennai.jpg|thumb|Headquarters of L&T Construction in Manapakkam, Chennai.]]\n\nChennai serves as the headquarters for some of Asia's largest engineering procurement and construction companies like [[VA Tech Wabag]], [[BGR Energy Systems Ltd|BGR Energy]], [[Larsen & Toubro|L&T Construction]], [[L&T Infrastructure Engineering Ltd.|L&T Infrastructure Engineering]], [[FLSmidth]], [[Ramboll]], [[Hyundai Engineering & Construction]], [[Hyundai Engineering (HEC)]], Shriram EPC.<ref>[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/infrastructure/shriram-epc-eyes-government-infrastructure-projects/articleshow/62048048.cms \"Shriram EPC eyes government infrastructure projects\"]</ref> Chennai has emerged as an Offshore Engineering hub due to the presence of Offshore Technology and Renewable Energy research institutions like [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], [[National Institute of Ocean Technology]], Center of Wind Energy Technology (C-WET), [[Indian Maritime University]], Tamil Nadu Energy Development Authority (TEDA), [[Anna University]] School of Energy, etc. Big EPC and Energy companies have set up their Engineering centres which include [[McDermott International]], [[DNV GL]], [[Saipem]], [[Rotork]], [[Technip]], [[Foster Wheeler]], [[Mott MacDonald]], [[Petrofac]], [[Vestas]], [[Siemens Gamesa]], [[Suzlon]], and others. Austrian company \"Austrian Energy and Environment\" have also a design office here besides local giant [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen & Toubro ECC]].\n\n==Automobiles==\n{{main|Automobile industry in Chennai}}\n{{see also|Automotive Corridor}}\n[[File:HyundaiChennai.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Hyundai's manufacturing plant at Irungattukottai near Sriperumbudur, [[Kanchipuram district]]]]\n\n[[Chennai]] is known as the [[Detroit of Asia]]. The city accounts for 60 per cent of India's automotive exports,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-economy/article1672471.ece |title=CII launches Chennai zone |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |date=19 October 2007 |accessdate=3 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=N. Madhavan |url=http://businesstoday.digitaltoday.in/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6059&issueid=34&Itemid=1 |title=India's Detroit |publisher=Businesstoday.digitaltoday.in |date=7 July 2008 |accessdate=3 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/12/04/AR2005120401094.html |title=Detroit's Next Big Threat |work=The Washington Post  |date= 5 December 2005|accessdate=3 March 2009 | first=Sebastian | last=Mallaby}}</ref> which leads it to be called as 'The Detroit of Asia'.<ref>[http://business.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jun/30/slide-show-1-auto-is-chennai-the-detroit-of-asia.htm Chennai, the Detroit of Asia?], rediff BUSINESS Shobha Warrier, 30 June 2010 13:01 IST</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704111704575354853980451636?mod=ITP_marketplace_0 A New Detroit Rises in India's South], THE WALL STREET JOURNAL By ERIC BELLMAN, 8 JULY 2010.</ref> Chennai has a market share of around 30% of India's automobile industry<ref name=\"autoindustry_share\">{{cite journal\n| last = Sivalingam\n| first = T\n|author2=Bhaskaran, E\n| title = IT applications in Automotive Industry\n| journal=GCMM 2004 1st international conference on manufacturing and management\n| page =20\n| year = 2004\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=v4Tm1of3UEcC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=chennai+auto+components+industry\n| accessdate =  3 September 2007\n| publisher=Alpha Science International, Limited\n| isbn = 978-81-7319-677-5}}</ref> and 35% of its auto components industry.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://dsir.nic.in/reports/ExpTechTNKL/Abs%20new/Automotive_Components.htm\n| title = Automotive Components\n| publisher = Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, Govt. of India\n| accessdate = 3 September 2007\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080430114520/http://www.dsir.nic.in/reports/ExpTechTNKL/Abs%20new/Automotive_Components.htm\n| archive-date = 30 April 2008\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref> A large number of the automotive companies including several global automotive companies such as [[BMW]], [[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], [[Nissan]], [[Renault]], [[Mitsubishi Motors|Mitsubishi]], [[TVS Motor Company]], [[Ashok Leyland]], [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]], [[Royal Enfield]], [[TI Cycles of India|TI Cycles]], [[TAFE Tractors|TAFE]], [[Dunlop Tyres|Dunlop]], [[Madras Rubber Factory|MRF]], [[Daimler AG|Daimler]], [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]], [[Michelin]], [[Bridgestone]], [[J. K. Organisation|JK Tyres]], [[Apollo Tyres]] and [[CEAT (company)|CEAT]] have manufacturing plants in and around Chennai. [[Mahindra & Mahindra]] have a manufacturing plant under construction in Cheyyar, which is about 100&nbsp;km from Chennai. The city is a major centre for the auto ancillary industry. Hyundai is in the process of setting up engine plant in the city. [[Ford]] is planning to invest $500&nbsp;million in Chennai plant.<ref name=\"Ford\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2008/01/09/stories/2008010951560200.htm|title=Ford India entering small car segment|work=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref> Several Petrochemical companies like Chennai Petro Chemicals Limited ([[Manali Refinery]]), [[Manali Petrochemicals]], Petro Araldite and [[Orchid Pharmaceuticals]] are situated in the outskirts of Chennai. Chennai will turn out close to 1.5&nbsp;million vehicles a year, more than any one U.S. state made last year [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704111704575354853980451636 A New Detroit Rises in India's South&nbsp;\u2013 WSJ.com].The city is also home to some of the world's largest Automotive R&D facilities in the world, which include [[Nissan]], [[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]], [[BMW]], [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] and [[Daimler AG|Daimler]]. It houses the world's second largest Research Valley- The Mahindra Research Valley.\n\nThe [[Heavy Vehicles Factory]], [[Avadi]] produces military vehicles, including India's [[main battle tank]]: ''[[Arjun MBT]]''. The Railway Coach building factory of the Indian Railways, the [[Integral Coach Factory]]<ref name=\"Integral_Coach_Factory\">{{cite web | title=Welcome to Official Website of ICF | url=http://www.icf.gov.in | accessdate=19 November 2005 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051123111146/http://icf.gov.in/ | archivedate=23 November 2005}}</ref> manufactures railway coaches and other rolling stock.\n\n==Banking and Finance==\n{{main|Banking in India|Banking and Finance in Chennai|Economy of Tamil Nadu}}\n{{see also|Global Financial Centres Index|Financial centre}}\n\n[[File:World Bank Office in Taramani, Chennai.jpg|thumb|right|World Bank Office in Chennai]]\nThe first modern bank in Chennai, [[Bank of Madras]] was started by the Britishers in 1843. It was followed by the opening of other banks namely - [[Arbuthnot & Co]], [[Bank of Chettinad]], [[Bank of Madura]], that were later merged under the supervision of RBI. The city serves as the headquarters for the second most number of banks and financial institutions in India, only next to the financial Capital [[Mumbai]]. The city has been tagged as the [[Banking Capital of India]], for its vibrant banking culture and trading. The city has emerged as an important center for banking and finance in the World Market. Chennai boasts a transaction volume which serves 1.5 billion people across the [[World]] through Back office operation. At present, it is home to four large national level [[commercial banks]] and many regional and state level [[co-operative]] banks. Several large financial companies and insurance companies are headquartered in Chennai.<ref name=itchennai2>{{cite news|title=Chennai emerging as India's Silicon Valley?\n|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Infotech/Software/Chennai_emerging_as_Indias_Silicon_Valley/articleshow/3000410.cms|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=1 May 2008|accessdate=17 May 2008|first=Rajesh|last=Chandramouli}}</ref> Prominent financial institutions, including the [[World Bank]], [[Standard Chartered Bank]], [[ABN AMRO]], [[Bank of America]], [[The Royal Bank of Scotland]], [[Goldman Sachs]], [[The Bank of New York Mellon|BNY Mellon]], [[Barclays]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[HSBC]], [[Wells Fargo]], [[Deutsche Bank]], [[ING Group]], [[Allianz]], [[Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corporation]], [[The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi UFJ]], [[Abu Dhabi Commercial Bank]], [[Asian Development Bank]], [[Credit Suisse]], [[BNP Paribas Fortis]], [[DBS Bank]], [[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group|ANZ]], and [[Citibank]] have [[back office]] and Development Center operations in the city. The city serves as a major back-up centre for operations of many banks and financial companies of the world.\n\nThe banking sector in Chennai is broadly classified into scheduled banks, non-scheduled banks and Foreign banks. All banks included in the Second Schedule to the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934 are Scheduled Banks. These banks comprise Scheduled Commercial Banks and Scheduled Co-operative Banks. Scheduled Co-operative Banks consist of Scheduled State Co-operative Banks and Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks. Scheduled Commercial Banks in Chennai are categorised into five different groups according to their ownership and/or nature of operation:\n* Nationalised Banks\n* Private Sector Banks\n* Foreign Banks\n* Regional Rural Banks\n* Small Finance Banks\nThe following are the list of Banks based in Chennai.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Bank Name !! Established !! Headquarter !! Branches !! [[Revenue]]s !! [[Asset|Total Assets]] !! Ref/Notes\n|-\n| [[Indian Bank]] || 1907 || [[Chennai]] || 2,836 || {{INRConvert|43414.34|c}} || {{INRConvert|394771|c}} || <ref>[http://www.indianbank.in/]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Indian Overseas Bank]] || 1937 || [[Chennai]] || 3,350 || {{INRConvert|43120.09|c}} || {{INRConvert|374436.76|c}} || <ref>[https://www.iob.in/]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Lakshmi Vilas Bank]] || 1926 || [[Chennai]] || 565 || {{INRConvert|2568.4|c}} 